title: User-submitted feedback for PMBC-CRASH-UI-DESIGN
body:
Katelyn Nichols (the.katelyn.nichols@gmail.com) reported an issue.


Name: "Designing for mobile and desktop"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/pmbc-crash-ui-design-v1/checkpoint/5

Course code: PMBC-CRASH-UI-DESIGN

Content:


    I'm not clear on what I'm supposed to do because the current Starbucks web and mobile app list all of the features that are listed for us to include in our wireframe. Are we completing a wireframe of what they currently have listed and we need to ensure that we have all of those features (even though all of the features listed are already on the mobile and web platforms)? Or are we supposed to be designing our own version? If it's our own version and we have to explain why we made the choices we did, the core reason would simply be because we're intentionally trying to do it differently than the website...because the way they have it set up currently looks like the most common way of setting up a website, and we'd want to follow that design layout for 'familiarity' for the customer. So I'm not clear what the assignment is wanting us to do. Could someone email me and explain?

title: User-submitted feedback for PMBC-PROD-MARKET-FIT
body:
Anna Cho (ajc2232@tc.columbia.edu) reported an issue.


Name: "Lean customer development"

Live URL: https://courses.thinkful.com/pmbc-prod-market-fit-v1/checkpoint/2

Course code: PMBC-PROD-MARKET-FIT

Content:


    Test the riskiest assumption Imagine youre going to build that babysitting matching service. Whats the hardest part? Which part has to succeed in order for the whole thing to succeed? Maybe you need to find ways to build trust between the parent and sitter. Maybe its that both parties want to ensure secure payments. Find that risky part and test it first.

Whats the smallest way to test it? It would be easy to just go and build a whole babysitting matching app with profiles and video chat and payments and more. But maybe theres a simpler thing you can do to test it without all the other parts. If you only saw a sitters references, would that be enough to make you trust this sitter?

Observe problems One way to find good hypotheses is to witness people in the act of solving their problem the old way. For instance, you could go to a friends home while they search for their own sitter. You notice they engage entirely through text messaging, which means you might be able to skip video chat and just do text chat for your app. Do the same for the sitters themselves. Watching them do the work is a great way to find opportunities for where you can improve the process.

Talk to customers Sometimes you cant find people in the act of solving these problems, so the next best thing you can do is talk to them about it. Well discuss interview techniques in a later lesson. For now, focus your interview on the way they solve the problem today and find the biggest issue within that.

Get expert advice As discussed before, you can always find people with experience in the field to see if they can give you insights. For example, find people who used to be babysitters and learn from their experience. You could contact people in related fields like nannies or home cleaners that likely face similar issues.

Should we vs**.** can we One place you can get hung up when coming up with solutions is on the question of can we solve the problem in a specific way. The answer is yes, you always can. With infinite time and developers, you could solve any problem. A better question is - should you do it this way? What are the pros and cons? And are there better ways of doing it



Should the first statement for each paragraph be bolded?
